you can use to outline them.

00:00:06.100 --> 00:00:09.280
We're going to use a grid to map all
your competitors on one slide and

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:11.870
position you as the leader.

00:00:11.870 --> 00:00:14.800
You're going to create something
like this for your final project.

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:17.900
Let's start by focusing on two
things that you really excel at.

00:00:17.900 --> 00:00:20.130
These are your competitive advantages.

00:00:20.130 --> 00:00:23.220
We'll use these to label
the two axes of the grid.

00:00:23.220 --> 00:00:25.990
And we want you to place
your main competitors here.

00:00:25.990 --> 00:00:30.410
But again, you'll be positioned as
the leader, right in this area.

00:00:30.410 --> 00:00:33.080
These competitive advantages
can be price versus value,

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:36.710
or you can write a specific
value to your customer.

00:00:36.710 --> 00:00:39.130
Maybe think of something
that your potential users or

00:00:39.130 --> 00:00:43.040
investors would be really,
really interested in, or excited about.

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:45.830
So we'll have to name our
two axes accordingly.

00:00:45.830 --> 00:00:49.660
So if it's price,
it will be low price and high price.

00:00:49.660 --> 00:00:51.950
Now let's say our value is innovation.

00:00:51.950 --> 00:00:55.195
We can have high innovation and
low innovation.

00:00:55.195 --> 00:00:57.181
Or you can choose something else.

00:00:57.181 --> 00:00:59.760
So for specific and generic,
let's talk about this.

